```

Key choices:
- Unit struct `DummyTool` (no fields) -- simplest possible implementation
- `_params` and `_ctx` prefixed with underscore -- signals intentionally unused
- `Box::pin(async { ... })` is the pattern for implementing the pinned-future return type
- Put the mock inside `#[cfg(test)]` so it's not compiled in release builds
- Test both the happy path (register + get + execute) and the error path (get nonexistent)

The `matches!` macro returns `bool` for pattern matching without needing a full `match` block. It's ideal for assertions and conditionals.

**Without matches! (verbose):**
```rust
let is_safe = match tier {
    PermissionTier::Safe => true,
    _ => false,
};
```

**With matches! (clean):**
```rust
let is_safe = matches!(tier, PermissionTier::Safe);
```

Power features:

```rust
// Multiple patterns with |
let is_readonly = matches!(
    tool_name,
    "file_read" | "grep" | "glob" | "web_fetch" | "ask_user"
);

// With guards
let is_destructive_reset = matches!(
    (subcommand, args),
    ("reset", a) if a.contains("--hard")
);

// In assertions (most common in tests)
assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Reject(_)));
assert!(matches!(result, RuleAction::Allow));

// In filter/find
let has_tool_call = events.iter().any(|e| matches!(e, StreamEvent::ToolCallStart));
```

Anti-pattern -- don't use `matches!` when you need the inner value:
```rust
// Bad: matches then extracts separately
if matches!(event, StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(_)) {
    if let StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(tc) = event { ... }
}

// Good: just use if-let
if let StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(tc) = event {
    // use tc directly
}
```

Use `strip_prefix()` and `strip_suffix()` which return `Option<&str>` -- no allocation, no off-by-one errors.

**Wrong way (manual slicing):**
```rust
fn strip_subshell(cmd: &str) -> &str {
    let trimmed = cmd.trim();
    if trimmed.starts_with("$(") && trimmed.ends_with(")") {
        return &trimmed[2..trimmed.len()-1]; // fragile, breaks on multibyte chars
    }
    trimmed
}
```

**Idiomatic:**
```rust
fn strip_subshell(cmd: &str) -> &str {
    let trimmed = cmd.trim();

    // $(...)
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix("$(") {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix(')') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }

    // `...`
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix('`') {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix('`') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }

    // (...)
    if let Some(inner) = trimmed.strip_prefix('(') {
        if let Some(stripped) = inner.strip_suffix(')') {
            return stripped.trim();
        }
    }

    trimmed
}
```

Advantages:
- Returns `&str` (borrows from input) -- zero allocation
- `strip_prefix` works on `&str` or `char` -- handles both
- No manual index math -- impossible to hit a multibyte char boundary
- Pattern reads top-to-bottom: try `$(...)`, then backticks, then parens

Each variant carries exactly the data relevant to that event. Use unit variants for signals, tuple variants for single payloads, struct variants for multiple fields.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub enum StreamEvent {
    /// Plain text -- carries the text content
    Text(String),
    /// Signal: tool call block detected (no data needed)
    ToolCallStart,
    /// Complete parsed tool call
    ToolCallComplete(ParsedToolCall),
    /// Partial tool call content for display during streaming
    ToolCallPartial(String),
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub enum ToolProgress {
    /// Completion percentage 0-100
    Percent(u8),
    /// Human-readable status message
    Status(String),
    /// Partial output streamed during execution
    PartialOutput(String),
}
```

Consumption pattern:
```rust
for event in parser.feed(chunk) {
    match event {
        StreamEvent::Text(text) => display_text(&text),
        StreamEvent::ToolCallStart => show_spinner(),
        StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(call) => {
            let result = registry.execute(&call.name, call.args(), &ctx).await?;
            display_result(&result);
        }
        StreamEvent::ToolCallPartial(partial) => update_spinner(&partial),
    }
}
```

Design rules:
- `#[derive(Debug, Clone)]` on all event enums -- they get logged, buffered, and inspected
- Use `String` not `&str` -- events outlive the chunk that produced them
- Prefer tuple variants `Foo(T)` over struct variants `Foo { data: T }` for single payloads
- Document each variant with `///` -- these are your API surface

**Original (imperative, C-style):**
```rust
fn tool_definitions(&self) -> Vec<ToolDefinition> {
    let mut defs = Vec::new();
    let keys: Vec<&String> = self.tools.keys().collect();
    for i in 0..keys.len() {
        let key = keys[i];
        let tool = self.tools.get(key).unwrap();
        let def = ToolDefinition {
            name: tool.name().to_string(),
            description: tool.description().to_string(),
            parameters: tool.parameters(),
        };
        defs.push(def);
    }
    return defs;
}
```

**Step 1: Replace index loop with for-in:**
```rust
fn tool_definitions(&self) -> Vec<ToolDefinition> {
    let mut defs = Vec::new();
    for tool in self.tools.values() {
        defs.push(ToolDefinition {
            name: tool.name().to_string(),
            description: tool.description().to_string(),
            parameters: tool.parameters(),
        });
    }
    defs
}
```

**Step 2: Replace push loop with iterator chain:**
```rust
fn tool_definitions(&self) -> Vec<ToolDefinition> {
    self.tools
        .values()
        .map(|t| ToolDefinition {
            name: t.name().to_string(),
            description: t.description().to_string(),
            parameters: t.parameters(),
        })
        .collect()
}
```

**What changed:**
- Removed mutable `Vec` + push pattern -> `.map().collect()`
- Removed `.keys()` + `.get().unwrap()` -> `.values()` directly
- Removed explicit `return` -> expression-based return
- No `unwrap()` anywhere -- `.values()` is infallible
- One expression, no intermediate bindings

**Original (nested if-let pyramid):**
```rust
fn get_param(params: &Value, key: &str) -> String {
    if let Some(val) = params.get(key) {
        if let Some(s) = val.as_str() {
            return s.to_string();
        } else {
            return "".to_string();
        }
    } else {
        return "".to_string();
    }
}

fn classify_git(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let subcommand = get_param(params, "subcommand");
    let args = get_param(params, "args");
    if subcommand == "status" || subcommand == "diff" || subcommand == "log" {
        return PermissionTier::Safe;
    } else if subcommand == "push" {
        return PermissionTier::Destructive;
    } else if subcommand == "reset" {
        if args.contains("--hard") {
            return PermissionTier::Destructive;
        }
        return PermissionTier::Write;
    }
    return PermissionTier::Write;
}
```

**Step 1: Flatten with `.and_then().unwrap_or()`:**
```rust
fn classify_git(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let subcommand = params.get("subcommand").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
    let args = params.get("args").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
    // ...
}
```

**Step 2: Replace if-else chain with match:**
```rust
fn classify_git(params: &Value) -> PermissionTier {
    let subcommand = params.get("subcommand").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");
    let args = params.get("args").and_then(|v| v.as_str()).unwrap_or("");

    match subcommand {
        "status" | "diff" | "log" | "show" | "remote" | "tag" => PermissionTier::Safe,
        "branch" => {
            if args.is_empty() || args.contains("-l") || args.contains("--list") {
                PermissionTier::Safe
            } else {
                PermissionTier::Write
            }
        }
        "add" | "commit" | "checkout" | "switch" | "merge" | "rebase" | "stash" => {
            PermissionTier::Write
        }
        "push" => PermissionTier::Destructive,
        "reset" => {
            if args.contains("--hard") {
                PermissionTier::Destructive
            } else {
                PermissionTier::Write
            }
        }
        _ => PermissionTier::Write,
    }
}
```

**What improved:**
- Helper function eliminated -- `.and_then().unwrap_or()` is a one-liner
- `match` is exhaustive with `_` -- no risk of forgetting a case
- Multi-pattern arms (`"status" | "diff" | ...`) reduce repetition
- Expression-based -- no `return` statements needed

**Original (AtomicBool -- polling only):**
```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicBool, Ordering};
use std::sync::Arc;

#[derive(Clone)]
struct CancelToken {
    cancelled: Arc<AtomicBool>,
}

impl CancelToken {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self { cancelled: Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(false)) }
    }
    fn cancel(&self) {
        self.cancelled.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
    }
    fn is_cancelled(&self) -> bool {
        self.cancelled.load(Ordering::SeqCst)
    }
}

// Problem: no way to .await cancellation -- must busy-poll
async fn wait_for_cancel(token: &CancelToken) {
    loop {
        if token.is_cancelled() { break; }
        tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(50)).await; // wasteful
    }
}
```

**Refactored (watch channel -- supports both polling and async wait):**
```rust
use tokio::sync::watch;

#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct CancelToken {
    sender: watch::Sender<bool>,
    receiver: watch::Receiver<bool>,
}

impl CancelToken {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        let (sender, receiver) = watch::channel(false);
        Self { sender, receiver }
    }

    pub fn cancel(&self) {
        self.sender.send(true).ok(); // .ok() ignores closed-channel error
    }

    pub fn is_cancelled(&self) -> bool {
        *self.receiver.borrow() // cheap lock-free read
    }

    pub fn clone_receiver(&self) -> watch::Receiver<bool> {
        self.receiver.clone()
    }
}

impl Default for CancelToken {
    fn default() -> Self { Self::new() }
}

// Now you can AWAIT cancellation:
async fn wait_for_cancel(mut rx: watch::Receiver<bool>) {
    while !*rx.borrow_and_update() {
        rx.changed().await.ok(); // wakes when value changes
    }
}
```

**What improved:**
- `rx.changed().await` wakes immediately on cancellation -- no polling loop
- `clone_receiver()` lets multiple observers share one token without Arc
- `borrow()` is still cheap for poll-style checks in hot loops
- Idempotent `cancel()` via `.ok()` -- safe to call multiple times
- `Default` impl for ergonomic construction

